\layout Abstract

We present radiative transfer models of the circumstellar environment of
 classical T
\protected_separator 
Tauri stars, concentrating on the formation of the H
\begin_inset Formula \( \alpha\)
\end_inset 

 emission.
 The wide variety of line profiles seen in observations are indicative of
 both inflow and outflow, and we therefore employ a circumstellar structure
 that includes both magnetospheric accretion and a disc wind.
 We perform systematic investigations of the model parameters for the wind
 and the magnetosphere to search for possible geometrical and physical condition
s
 which lead to the types of profiles seen in observations.
 We find that the hybrid models can reproduce the wide range profile types
 seen is observations, and that the most common profile types observed occupy
 a large volume of parameter space.
 Conversely, the most infrequently observed profile morphologies require
 a very specific set of models parameters.
 We investigate the wind contribution to the line profile as a function
 of model parameters, and examine the reliability of H
\begin_inset Formula \( \alpha\)
\end_inset 

 as a mass accretion diagnostic.
 Finally, we examine the H
\begin_inset Formula \( \alpha\)
\end_inset 

 spectroscopic classification used by Reipurth et.
\protected_separator 
al, and discuss the basic physical conditions that are required to reproduce
 the profiles in each classified type.
