In the currently favoured model of accretion in CTTS, the accretion disc
 is disrupted by the magnetosphere, which channels the gas from the disc
 onto the stellar surface (e.g., 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \citealt{uchida:1985}

\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \citealt{koenigl:1991}

\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \citealt{cameron:1993}

\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \citealt{shu:1994}

\end_inset 

).
 This picture is supported by recent measurements of strong (
\begin_inset Formula \( \sim 10^{3}\mathrm{G}\)
\end_inset 

) magnetic fields in CTTS (e.g., 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \citealt{johns-krull:1999}

\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \citealt{symington:2005b}

\end_inset 

) and by radiative transfer models which reproduce the gross characteristics
 of observed profiles for some TTS (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \citealt*{muzerolle:2001}

\end_inset 

).
 In particular the magnetospheric accretion (MA) model explains blue-ward
 asymmetric emission line profiles as resulting from the partial occultation
 of the flow by the stellar photosphere, while inverse P
\protected_separator 
Cygni profiles in the MA model result from inflowing material at near free-fall
 velocities seen projected against hotspots on the stellar surface.
\layout Standard

Despite these successes, the overwhelming observational evidence for outflow
 in the CTTS suggests that the MA model is only one component of a complex
 circumstellar environment.
 Clearly, one must include the contribution of any wind/jet flow if one
 wishes to both accurately predict the mass-accretion rate and also determined
 the mass-loss rate of CTTS via emission profile modelling.
 The first attempt in this direction was made by 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \citet{alencar:2005}

\end_inset 

 who demonstrated that the observed H
\begin_inset Formula \( \alpha\)
\end_inset 

, H
\begin_inset Formula \( \beta\)
\end_inset 

 and Na
\protected_separator 
D lines of RW Aur are better reproduced by the radiative transfer model
 which included a collimated disc-wind arising from near the inner edge
 of the accretion disc.
\layout Standard

