The radiative transfer model
\layout Standard


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sec:radiative-transfer-model}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

We have extended the 
\shape smallcaps 
TORUS
\shape default 
 radiative transfer code (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \citealt{harries:2000}

\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \citealt{kurosawa:2004a}

\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \citealt{symington:2005}

\end_inset 

) to include the multiple circumstellar components described above.
 In previous calculations 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \citep{symington:2005}

\end_inset 

, the model was used with a three-dimensional (3-D) adaptive mesh refinement
 (AMR) grid to investigate the line variability associated with rotational
 modulation of complex geometrical configurations of magnetospheric inflow
 (see also 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \citealt*{kurosawa:2005a}

\end_inset 

).
 We modified the code to handle the a two-dimensional (2-D) density distribution
,
 and restricted our models to be axi-symmetric.
 Note that the velocity field is still in 3-D -- the third component can
 be calculated by using symmetry for a given value of azimuthal angle.
\layout Standard

The computation of H
\begin_inset Formula \( \alpha\)
\end_inset 

 is divided in two parts: (1)
\protected_separator 
the source function calculation (
\begin_inset Formula \( S_{\nu}\)
\end_inset 

) and (2)
\protected_separator 
the observed flux/profile calculation.
 In the first process, we have used the method of 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \citet{klein:1978}

\end_inset 

 (see also 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \citealt{rybicki:1978}

\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \citealt{hartmann:1994}

\end_inset 

) in which the Sobolev approximation method is applied.
 The population of the bound states of hydrogen are assumed to be in statistical
 equilibrium, and the gas to be in radiative equilibrium.
 Our hydrogen atom model consist of 14 bound states and a continuum.
 Readers are refer to 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \citet{harries:2000}

\end_inset 

 for details.
\layout Standard

Monte Carlo radiative transfer (e.g. 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \citealt{hillier:1991}

\end_inset 

), under the Sobolev approximation, can be used when (1)
\protected_separator 
a large velocity gradient is present in the gas flow, and (2)
\protected_separator 
the intrinsic line width is negligible compared to the Doppler broadening
 of the line.
 In our earlier models (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \citealt{harries:2000}

\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \citealt{symington:2005}

\end_inset 

), this method was adopted since these conditions are satisfied.
 However, as noted and demonstrated by 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \citet{muzerolle:2001}

\end_inset 

, even with a moderate mass-accretion rate (
\begin_inset Formula \( ~10^{-7}\,\mathrm{M_{\sun}\,
yr^{-1}}\)
\end_inset 

), Stark broadening becomes important in the optically thick H
\begin_inset Formula \( \alpha\)
\end_inset 

 line. 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \citet{muzerolle:2001}

\end_inset 

 also pointed out that the observed H
\begin_inset Formula \( \alpha\)
\end_inset 

 profiles from CTTS typically have the wings extending to 
\begin_inset Formula \( 500\,\mathrm{km\, s^{-1}}\)
\end_inset 

(e.g.
\protected_separator 

\begin_inset LatexCommand \citealt{edwards:1994}

\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \citealt{reipurth:1996}

\end_inset 

) which cannot be explained by the infall velocity alone.
\layout Standard

We have implemented the broadening mechanism following the formalism described
 by 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \citet{muzerolle:2001}

\end_inset 

.
 First, the emission and absorption profiles are replaced from the Doppler
 to the Voigt profile, which is defined as: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation} 
  H\left(a,y\right) \equiv
  \frac{a}{\pi}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\frac{e^{-y'^{2}}}{\left(y-y'\right)^{2}+a^{2}}\, dy'  
  \label{eq:voigt_profile_def}
\end{equation}
\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula \( a=\Gamma/4\pi\Delta\nu_{\mathrm{D}}\)
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula \( y=\left(\nu-\nu_{0}\right)/\Delta\nu_{\mathrm{D}}\)
\end_inset 

, and 
\begin_inset Formula \( y'=\left(\nu'-\nu_{0}\right)/\Delta\nu_{\mathrm{D}}\)
\end_inset 

 (c.f. 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \citealt{mihalas:1978}

\end_inset 

). 
\begin_inset Formula \( \nu_{0}\)
\end_inset 

 is the line centre frequency, and 
\begin_inset Formula \( \Delta\nu_{\mathrm{D}}\)
\end_inset 

 is the Doppler line width of hydrogen atom (due to its thermal motion)
 which is given by 
\begin_inset Formula \( \Delta\nu_{\mathrm{D}}=\left(2kT/m_{\mathrm{H}}\right)^{1/2}\times\left(\nu_{0}/c\right)\)
\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula \( m_{\mathrm{H}}\)
\end_inset 

 is the mass of a hydrogen atom.
 The damping constant 
\begin_inset Formula \( \Gamma\)
\end_inset 

, which depends on the physical condition of the gas, is parameterised by
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \citet*{vernazza:1973}

\end_inset 

 as follows: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray} 
  \Gamma & = & C_{\mathrm{rad}} + C_{\mathrm{vdW}}
  \left(\frac{n_{\mathrm{HI}}}{10^{16}\,\mathrm{cm^{-3}}}\right)
  \left(\frac{T}{5000\,\mathrm{K}}\right)^{0.3}\nonumber \\
  &  & + \,
  C_{\mathrm{Stark}}\left(\frac{n_{e}}{10^{12}\,\mathrm{cm^{-3}}}\right)^{2/3}
  \label{eq:dampimg_constant_def}
\end{eqnarray}
\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula \( n_{\mathrm{H\, I}}\)
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \( n_{e}\)
\end_inset 

 are the number density of neutral hydrogens and that of free electrons.
