 method (c.f. 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \citealt{mihalas:1978}

\end_inset 

) for computing the observed flux as a function of frequence.
 The integration of the flux is performed in the cylindrical coordinate
 system 
\begin_inset Formula \( \left(p,\, q,\, t\right)\)
\end_inset 

 which is obtained by rotating the original stellar coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula \( \left(\rho,\,\phi,\, z\right)\)
\end_inset 

 around the 
\begin_inset Formula \( y\)
\end_inset 

 axis by the inclination of the line of sight.
 Note that the 
\begin_inset Formula \( t\)
\end_inset 

-axis coincides with the line of sight with this rotation.
 The observed flux (
\begin_inset Formula \( F_{\nu}\)
\end_inset 

) is given by: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation} 
  F_{\nu}=\frac{1}{4\pi d^{2}}
  \int_{0}^{p_{\mathrm{max}}}\int_{0}^{2\pi}p\,\sin q\,
  I_{\nu}\mathrm{\, d}q\,\mathrm{d}p
  \label{eq:flux_integral}
\end{equation}
\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula \( d\)
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula \( p_{\mathrm{max}}\)
\end_inset 

, and 
\begin_inset Formula \( I_{\nu}\)
\end_inset 

 are the distance to an observer, the maximum extent to the model space
 in the projected (rotated) plane, and the specific intensity (
\begin_inset Formula \( I_{\nu}\)
\end_inset 

) in the direction on observer at the outer boundary.
 For a given ray along 
\begin_inset Formula \( t\)
\end_inset 

, the specific intensity is given by: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation} 
       I_{\nu} = I_{0}e^{-\tau_{\infty}} + 
           \int_{t_{0}}^{t_{\infty}}S_{\nu}\left(t\right)\,
                e^{-\tau}\mathrm{d}\tau
 \label{eq:formal_sol_integral}
\end{equation}
\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula \( I_{0}\)
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \( S_{\nu}\)
\end_inset 

 are the intensity at the boundary on the opposite to the observer and the
 source function (
\begin_inset Formula \( \eta_{\nu}/\chi_{\nu}\)
\end_inset 

) of the stellar atmosphere/wind at a frequency 
\begin_inset Formula \( \nu\)
\end_inset 

.
 For a ray which intersects with the stellar core, 
\begin_inset Formula \( I_{0}\)
\end_inset 

 is computed from the stellar atmosphere model of 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \citet{kurucz:1979}

\end_inset 

 as described in section
\protected_separator 

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Continuum-Source}

\end_inset 

